Different service (`epay_reports_service`), different failure — but a clear one.

## Root cause

You changed the PVC's access mode in the chart, and **PVC specs are immutable after creation**. The diff in the error says it exactly:

```
- AccessModes: ["ReadWriteMany"]    ← what's live on the cluster now
+ AccessModes: ["ReadWriteOnce"]    ← what your chart now wants
```

The live `report-pvc` was created as `ReadWriteMany`. Your updated `values.yaml`/template now renders `ReadWriteOnce`. Kubernetes forbids patching any PVC field except `resources.requests` (grow) and `volumeAttributesClassName` on a bound claim — so Helm's attempt to change `accessModes` is rejected, and the upgrade fails.

Let me confirm what the chart is currently set to, so you fix the right side:The chart hardcodes `ReadWriteOnce`, but the live PVC is `ReadWriteMany`. First confirm the live state and — importantly — figure out **which mode is actually correct** for this service before you change anything.

```bash
oc get pvc report-pvc -n <report-namespace> -o jsonpath='{.spec.accessModes}{" phase="}{.status.phase}{"\n"}'
# (namespace is wherever RELEASE_NAME=report deploys — likely dev-transaction or a dev-report ns)

# Does more than one pod mount it? That decides RWO vs RWX:
oc get pods -n <report-namespace> -o json \
  | jq -r '.items[] | select([.spec.volumes[]?.persistentVolumeClaim.claimName] | index("report-pvc")) | .metadata.name'
```

Which mode you want dictates the fix:

- **If the report service runs >1 replica** (multiple pods writing the same report volume) → it genuinely needs **ReadWriteMany**. The chart is wrong; the live PVC is right. → **Fix A** (change the chart back to RWX).
- **If it's a single replica** → RWO is fine and arguably better, but you still can't patch the existing PVC. → **Fix B** (recreate the PVC).

## Fix A — Chart should be RWX (most likely, given it was created RWX)

Edit `dev/charts/epay_reports_service/templates/pvc.yaml` line 7:

```yaml
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteMany
```

This makes the chart match the live PVC, so Helm's next patch is a no-op on that field and the upgrade proceeds. **No data loss, no PVC recreation** — the cleanest path. Given the PVC was originally created RWX (likely deliberately, because reports often need shared read/write across replicas), this is probably the right answer and someone introduced the RWO by mistake.

Also fix the CRLF line endings while you're in there — this file has `^M` (Windows) endings, which can cause subtle YAML/templating issues:
```bash
sed -i 's/\r$//' dev/charts/epay_reports_service/templates/pvc.yaml
```

## Fix B — You truly want RWO (only if single-replica and you intend the change)

The PVC can't be patched, so it must be recreated. This **deletes the volume** — back up first if the report data matters.

```bash
NS=<report-namespace>
# 1. Back up any data on the volume (mount via a temp pod or copy out) if needed
# 2. Scale down whatever mounts it
oc scale deploy report -n $NS --replicas=0
# 3. Delete the PVC (and its PV if reclaimPolicy=Retain, clean up the released PV after)
oc delete pvc report-pvc -n $NS
# 4. Re-run the pipeline — Helm recreates report-pvc as ReadWriteOnce, scales back up
```

Caveat: if the underlying storage class doesn't support RWX at all, that's a separate reason the RWO change may have been attempted — but the immutability error is the blocker regardless, and Fix A sidesteps it entirely.

## Recommendation

Go with **Fix A** unless you have a specific reason to move this volume to RWO. It's zero-risk, no data loss, and matches the volume's original provisioning. Confirm replica count with the `oc get pods` check above — if you see more than one report pod, RWX is definitely required and Fix A is mandatory.

## After the fix

```bash
# chart now matches live — verify
grep -A1 accessModes dev/charts/epay_reports_service/templates/pvc.yaml   # expect ReadWriteMany (Fix A)

# re-run pipeline, then:
oc get pvc report-pvc -n <report-namespace>          # Bound, correct mode
helm status report -n <report-namespace> | grep STATUS   # deployed
```

One thing worth doing across the board: this is the third chart-vs-cluster drift you've hit in a row (CRB ownership, storage class, now PVC access mode). When you get a moment, a `helm diff upgrade` (if the helm-diff plugin is available in your CI image) run as a **dry-run gate** before the real deploy would catch all three classes of problem before they fail a live pipeline. Worth adding to the deploy template given the ~55-repo scale.
